<br>
run 3<br>
regen 3<br>
SCM 3<br>
<br>
And somewhere we have to stick in pet hold, contigent on how much you raid. (More you raid, sooner you should get it. If you are looking for an endorsement from me to join my guild, you better have it immediately hehe)<br>
<br>
Then the question is which to work on first:<br>
<br>
Subtelty 3 and/or SCF4 (since it's generally considered crits don't do (much) extra aggro)<br>
<br>
or QS 2 and/or suspend companion 2<br>
<br>
On my list I sugest a little bit of both. I'll modify it a little: Something like subtlety 1, QS 1, MC1, QS2, SCF 4, subtelety 3 , suspend 2. If you are a disciple of IR, stick that in there somewhere too <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Some days I'm seriously hurting on aggro and glad I have subtlety 3, sometimes (especially solo/duo) I'm seriously hurting on mana, when I'm glad I have QS and suspend companion.<br>
<br>
Another way to look at the argument about QS3: once you have QS2 and have mastered cannibilization, all that mana isn't going to do you much good if you keep stealing aggro or you can't dump your mana fast enough (which si sorta what SCF lets you do: do damage faster). I'd strongly urge you to use those 9 points you are considering putting into QS3 into subtelty or SCF first. OTOH if you never cannabilize and don't have enough QS to do it well, in some situations you won't have enough mana to make subtelety mean anything. Some QS is good too. <p>Master Cydmab Promethean<br>
Arch Convoker of Morell Thule<br>
Fury's Edge</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jochangaladar>Jochan Galadar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 943<br> <font color=#333333>(2/17/03 3:06:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=540.topic&index=50>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Optimal AA path for magicians</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'd strongly urge you to use those 9 points you are considering putting into QS3 into subtelty or SCF first.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sage advice, to be sure.  I would recommend getting a Summoning Haste item if you can.  I personally maxed the skill so I would have one less piece of equipment to hunt down.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>At 15 kills per 1094/4282 seconds, that's average 1:12 per fight, and 3:30 downtime in between fights. I kill about 1 mob every 4:42. I probably could lower my downtime by cannipetting with MSII, I'm just lazy. I'm curious how long it really takes for you to kill something with reclaim chaining?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That's a difficult question to answer.  Using reclaim chaining <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>solo</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> in PoP is very very difficult because I won't have a chance at getting an effective enough pet root until 65.  With a distractor partner the 57 Earth pet is doable.  I would have to do a log to verify battle time.  I will have to get back to you on that one, then.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You should have been able to hold off the mob with chained pets while nuking hard<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
That is what was attempted.  One magician overaggroed and died.  The other two ran oom.  I did not say that I died FM.  What I did say is that I died because I cannot solo two frogs.  I will admit that my focus was to keep the frogs busy for as long as I could, by making sure I always had a pet up tanking.  The point of my story is that we lost because most of us went OOM.  If we hadn't, we would have prevailed.  The evocation strategy has drawbacks when things go bad, or at least when things are not ideal.<br>
<br>
Goladus, you have made your point.  In situations where mana is plentiful, Improved Reclaim and pet canni are redundant and can potentially lower dps rates in &quot;balanced&quot; grouping configurations.  Also, in Evocation-style soloing circumstances, the biggest factors are total mana pool and tweaked dps.  Improved Reclaim and Quick Summoning do not assist this style during a combat, although QS can benefit in reducing downtime in between combats. IR's biggest strength is when things go bad, mana is at a premium, and/or the pets themselves need to tank.<br>
<br>
Thank you for your feedback. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <br><font color=#333333>- </font><a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower>The Magician's Tower</a><font color=#333333> - </font><a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30>Magician Skills</a> <font color=#333333> - </font><a href="http://www.magecompendium.com/">The Mage Compendium</a><font color=#333333> - </font>  <br><br><table border=0 align=center><tr><td align=center><a href="http://login.ezboard.com/BBSSystem.showUserPaymentScreen" target="_blank">Upgrade your account to ezSupporter...</a></td><td><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/image/spacer.gif" width=15 height=1 border=0></td><td align=center><a href="http://login.ezboard.com/BBSSystem.showUserPaymentScreen" target="_blank">...and never see another ad or pop-up again</a></td></tr></table><CENTER><!-- START BOTTOM AD SCRIPT -->
